# MEMORY MANAGEMENT

## Understanding Memory Management:

On a very surface level, with respect to data structures, memory management is controlling and organizing the memory. It works on how you allocate memory, how the memory is used and freed.
Under this comes the wide-known distinction: understanding when and how memory is assigned to variables and data structures- via static and dynamic memory allocation

---

## Static Memory Allocation:

Understand that static means unchanging- in other words fixed
So static memory allocation involves a fixed size and type of memory

This introduces us on a better ground to static memory allocation which involves:

* Memory being allocated by the compiler
* Exact size and type of the memory must be known at compile time
* Memory allocated- cannot be altered during run time
* Memory is allocated in the stack area

**Useful:**
When the data size is fixed and known before processing

**Not useful:**

* Memory under utilization or over utilization
* Memory cannnot be deleted only contents can be rewritten

**Use cases:** ( Simple terms: when you need speed and predictability)

* Critical performance requirements: Competitive programming, real-time data processing
* Embedded systems: systems with limited memory
* Deterministic behaviour

Eg: int a,

---

## Dynamic Memory Allocation

Dynamic means changing
Indicating that the sizeof memory being allocated can change
Memory is allocated during runtime which is the program execution time
Memory can be obtained and released during program execution

**Advantages**

**Disadvantages**

**Necessity:**

* Input size is unknown or needs to grow and shrink
* Complex data structures
* Optimized memory usage- when we dont want to under or over utilize
* Memory persistence outside the function scope as static memory disappears after the function ends

---

## Application in Python:

You dont explicitly manage memory

Python has three important workings:

* Dynamic memory allocation by default
* Garbage collection
* Heap based object storage

Every variable created is allocated dynamically and managed by python internally
Memory gets allocated to the heap -> Python track reference -> Remove it when not used ( all of this is taken care by python without interference of the user)

Static allocation : Behaviour runs similar to fixed-size data structures: tuples

